---
import FrameworkLayout from '../../layouts/FrameworkLayout.astro';
import { url } from '../../utils';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "MedicalWebPage",
  "name": "Phase 3: Implementation — Hospital Acupuncture Implementation",
  "description": "Execute the acupuncture or acupressure implementation plan using evidence-based strategies: education, opinion leaders, training, management engagement, and staged rollout.",
  "url": "https://hospitalacupuncture.com/framework/implementation/",
  "lastReviewed": "2026-04",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Dr Zhen Zheng",
    "affiliation": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "RMIT University" }
  }
};
---

<FrameworkLayout
  title="Implementation"
  description="Execute the plan using evidence-based implementation strategies, training, management engagement, and staged rollout."
  phaseNumber={3}
  bottomLine="Successful hospital acupuncture implementation requires coordinating both internal factors (organisational structure, communication, readiness) and external factors (patient needs, peer networks, policy). Use proven implementation strategies — opinion leaders are the most effective at 12% behaviour change — and start with a controlled pilot before scaling."
  schema={schema}
>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Successful acupuncture/acupressure implementation requires both internal and external
    enablers. Internal factors encompass organisation characteristics, networks and communication,
    climate for change, and readiness for change. External factors cover patient needs, peer
    pressure, organisational networks, and external policy.
  </p>
  <p>
    This phase translates the preparation work into action, using the Consolidated Framework
    for Implementation Research (CFIR) constructs as a guide. While PONV acupressure serves as
    the worked example, the strategies apply to any hospital acupuncture programme.
  </p>

  <!-- Organisational Structure -->
  <h2>1. Structure of the Organisation</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>CFIR: Structural Characteristics</summary>
    <p>
      Implementation scope determines which departments and units must be involved. The broader
      the intervention window, the more coordination is required.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>PONV example:</strong> If acupressure wristbands are used for 24 hours peri-surgically,
      then staff from admission, theatre, recovery, and the wards will all be involved.
      Coordination and communication among those units are essential.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>General principle:</strong> Ensure all key stakeholders are part of the team.
      Map the patient journey through your organisation and identify every handover point
      where the intervention must be communicated, maintained, or documented.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Priority and Goals -->
  <h2>2. Priority and Goals</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Aligning Implementation with Clinician Priorities</summary>
    <p>
      Research shows that alignment between an intervention and existing clinician priorities is
      a stronger predictor of implementation effectiveness than the strength of the evidence
      itself.
    </p>
    <p>To achieve alignment:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Communicate how the intervention supports goals staff already care about
        (e.g., patient satisfaction, reduced medication burden, shorter recovery times)</li>
      <li>Provide regular feedback on outcomes that matter to frontline clinicians</li>
      <li>Frame the intervention as enhancing &mdash; not replacing &mdash; existing practice</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <!-- Implementation Strategies -->
  <h2>3. Implementation Strategies</h2>

  <details open>
    <summary>Evidence-Based Strategies (Grimshaw, 2012)</summary>
    <p>
      A systematic review by Grimshaw (2012) quantified the effectiveness of common
      implementation strategies. The table below shows each strategy with its measured
      effect and a hospital acupuncture example:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Strategy</th>
          <th>Effectiveness</th>
          <th>Hospital Acupuncture Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Printed educational material</td>
          <td>4.3%</td>
          <td>Evidence summary handouts, point location guides, patient information sheets
            distributed to all relevant clinical areas</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Educational meetings</td>
          <td>6%</td>
          <td>Grand rounds presentations, ward in-service sessions, lunchtime seminars
            covering evidence, technique, and workflow integration</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Local opinion leaders</td>
          <td>12% <span class="grade grade-high">High</span></td>
          <td>Respected senior clinicians who advocate for acupuncture/acupressure,
            demonstrate technique, and mentor colleagues</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Audit and feedback</td>
          <td>5%</td>
          <td>Regular reports on intervention uptake, patient outcomes, and compliance
            fed back to clinical teams</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      Effectiveness refers to median absolute improvement in compliance with desired practice.
      Strategies are most effective when combined.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Training -->
  <h2>4. Training</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>CFIR: Access to Knowledge and Information</summary>
    <p>
      Training is essential for all staff involved in delivery, monitoring, and documentation.
      The POPA4Ease project developed three differentiated training packages:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Package</th><th>Audience</th><th>Content Focus</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Package A</strong></td>
          <td>Direct intervention deliverers (nurses, acupuncturists)</td>
          <td>Point location, technique, dosage, contraindications, documentation</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Package B</strong></td>
          <td>Supervising clinicians (anaesthetists, surgeons)</td>
          <td>Evidence base, patient selection, safety monitoring, escalation protocols</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Package C</strong></td>
          <td>Ward and support staff</td>
          <td>Awareness of intervention, monitoring for displacement or adverse events,
            documentation requirements</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Supplement formal training with on-the-job mentoring: pair trained staff with new
      adopters for the first several patients.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Management Engagement -->
  <h2>5. Engaging Management</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>CFIR: Leadership Engagement</summary>
    <p>
      Leadership engagement &mdash; defined as the commitment, involvement, and accountability
      of leaders and managers &mdash; is required at three levels:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Level</th><th>Role in Implementation</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Executive leadership</strong></td>
          <td>Authorise the programme, allocate resources, signal organisational priority</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Middle management</strong></td>
          <td>Facilitate cross-departmental coordination, resolve operational barriers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Frontline management</strong></td>
          <td>Support daily practice, adjust rosters, reinforce training, provide immediate feedback</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>

  <!-- Assessment -->
  <h2>6. Assessment and Evaluation</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>CFIR: Reflecting and Evaluating</summary>
    <p>
      Define outcome measures before launch. Decide what to measure, how to track it, and
      how often to review:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clinical outcomes</strong> &mdash; condition incidence rates, rescue medication use, patient-reported outcomes</li>
      <li><strong>Process measures</strong> &mdash; intervention uptake rate, correct technique adherence, documentation completeness</li>
      <li><strong>Staff measures</strong> &mdash; confidence levels, satisfaction, feedback on workflow integration</li>
      <li><strong>Patient measures</strong> &mdash; satisfaction, willingness to recommend, adverse events</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Use regular audits to identify and correct implementation drift early. The Joanna Briggs
      Institute's PACES online audit tool provides a structured approach to clinical audit.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Execution -->
  <h2>7. Execute the Implementation</h2>

  <details open>
    <summary>Staged Rollout Approach</summary>
    <p>
      Rather than organisation-wide launch, use a staged approach to manage risk and build
      confidence:
    </p>
    <h4>Step 1: Practice Runs</h4>
    <p>
      Conduct dry runs with simulated patients or willing volunteers. Identify workflow issues,
      timing problems, and documentation gaps before any real patient contact.
    </p>
    <h4>Step 2: Pilot Implementation</h4>
    <p>
      Start with a single ward, unit, or surgical list. Collect data intensively, debrief
      weekly, and refine protocols based on real-world experience.
    </p>
    <h4>Step 3: Controlled Expansion</h4>
    <p>
      Expand to additional units one at a time, using lessons from the pilot. Each new unit
      benefits from refined protocols and trained mentors from earlier stages.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tip:</strong> Limiting initial scope reduces resistance and allows early
      adopters to become advocates before sceptical colleagues must engage.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- External Resources -->
  <div class="downloads">
    <h3>Phase 3 Resources</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://cfirguide.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CFIR Guide</a> &mdash; constructs and matching tools for implementation research</li>
      <li><a href="https://jbi.global/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Joanna Briggs Institute PACES</a> &mdash; online clinical audit tool</li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Training package templates</a></li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Audit and feedback report template</a></li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Staged rollout planning checklist</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

</FrameworkLayout>
